  "texts": [
    "Schematically, I will argue that a very promising way to defend HEC involves claims about the nature of intentional actions -specifically, those involved in cognitive offloading -that one side of the action theoretic controversy denies.",
    "What defenders of HEC should claim, I suggest, is that actions can sometimes be constitutive of cognition and, considered as such, are constituted by more than the movements of an agent's body.",
    "More specifically, they should endorse the view that the actions by which a cognitive agent achieves offloading constitutively depend on the way bodily movements fit into a wider causal network centred on the agent.",
    "Specifying this wider causal context uncovers a distinctively cognitive pattern in events and processes that considered separately lack identifying 'marks of the cognitive'.",
    "It is only as these distributed elements come together to constitute an act of offloading that their cognitive status comes into view."
  ],
